symbolletters: P represents the statement "More people have been to London than I have"
variables: x represents the subject (the person speaking)

Translation: ∀x(Px → ∃y(Py ∧ morePeopleThany(x,y)))

Explanation:

• ∀x(Px) means "For all x, P is true"
• Px means "x has been to London"
• → means "implies"
• ∃y(Py) means "There exists a y such that Py is true"
• Py means "y has been to London"
• ∃y(morePeopleThany(x,y)) means "There exists a y such that more people have been to London than x and y"
• morePeopleThany(x,y) means "The number of people who have been to London is greater than the sum of x and y"
• This statement can be translated into a formal logical system using predicate logic. It states that for all values of x (representing a person), if Px (the person has been to London) is true, then there exists a y (another person) such that Py (the other person has been to London) and morePeopleThany(x,y) (more people have been to London than x and y) are both true.
